5. The form of the Annali is, as the name indicates, strictly chronological. The events ol each year are told by themselves, so that any independent series os events can be read in connec- tion only by taking in succession several detached passages3 to this rule there are but one or two exceptions (ag. VI. 31-37). As has been already said, the extant portions ol the work con- sist of two distinct parts, separated bya gap os four books. This gap covers the reign of Caligula and most of that of Claudius (A.D. 37 to 54), while the two extant portions com- prise the reigns of Tiberius and Nero respectively. The accounts os these two reigns are preserved nearly complete. The present edition contains the first part, the reign os Tibe- rius, comprising the first six books, ol which, however, nearly the whole os the fifth book and perhaps a quarter ol the sixth are missing. The missing portions contained the year 30 with the greater part of 29 and 31, the reign of Tiberius extending srorn nn. 14 to 37.
